 practice is both necessary and possible in the neoliberal world. Drawing on the author’s unique experience, core areas of practice with children and families are covered, including real life case studies, key point summaries and suggestions for further reading. The essential argument is for an emancipatory practice geared to meeting immediate needs, as well as having some vision of a future, more socially just and equal, society. The book will be invaluable to undergraduate and postgraduate social work students, experienced practitioners, educators, managers and policy makers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aFamily social workzGreat Britain. 0aSocial servicezGreat Britain. 0aSocial work with childrenzGreat Britain. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aJordan, Bill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995z9783111196213oZDB-23-BUPP0 cprintz978144730502640uhttps://doi.org/10.56687/9781447314219?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447314219423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447314219/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-BUPPc1995d2013